Number of flat responders:

sum(ecl_dat$flat)
## [1] 0

ecl_dat <- ecl_dat[!ecl_dat$flat, ]

Number of participants who failed first attention check:

# number of participants who failed attention1 check
sum(ecl_dat$attention1 != 2)
## [1] 1
# remove those who failed attention1 check
ecl_dat <- ecl_dat[ecl_dat$attention1=="2",]

Number of participants who failed second attention check:

# number who failed attention2 check
sum(!(ecl_dat$attentionOrange == 0 & ecl_dat$attentionBlue == 0 & ecl_dat$attentionBulb == 1))
## [1] 25
pass_attention2 <- (ecl_dat$attentionOrange == 0 & ecl_dat$attentionBlue == 0 & ecl_dat$attentionBulb == 1)

# remove those who failed attention2 check
ecl_dat <- ecl_dat[pass_attention2, ]

Number of outliers for total time taken:

# outliers for Total Time taken for survey

2 Summary Statistics

  • relationBlue: likelihood that blue caused bulb to light up
  • relationOrange: likelihood that orange caused bulb to light up
  • relationOrangeBlue: likelihood that both caused bulb to light up
  • expBlue: likelihood that agent expected blue to cause bulb to light up
  • expOrange: likelihood that agent expected orange to cause bulb to light up
  • expBoth: likelihood that agent expected both to cause bulb to light up
  • desire: likelihood that agent desired to bulb to light up
  • knowledge: likelihood that agent knew how to turn on the bulb
# normalizing desire and knowledge variables
ecl_dat$desire <- (ecl_dat$desire - 1)/8
ecl_dat$knowledge <- (ecl_dat$knowledge1 - 1)/8
# note these are all normalized ratings which were originally measured using Likert scales
human_cause_data <- gather.keep(ecl_dat, var.to.gather = c("relationBlueNorm", "relationOrangeNorm", "relationOrangeBlueNorm"), keep = c("id", "condition"), key = "structure",value="likelihood")

human_expectation_data <- gather.keep(ecl_dat, var.to.gather = c("expBlueNorm", "expOrangeNorm","expBothNorm"), keep = c("id", "condition"), key = "structure",value="likelihood")

human_desire_data <- gather.keep(ecl_dat, var.to.gather = c("desire"), keep = c("id", "condition"), key = "structure",value="likelihood")

human_knowledge_data <- gather.keep(ecl_dat, var.to.gather = c("knowledge"), keep = c("id", "condition"), key = "structure",value="likelihood")
set.seed(100)

4 Visualizing Participants’ Inferences

4.1 Causal Inferences

The bar graphs shows participants’ causal inferences for:

  • the hypothesis that pushing the blue box caused the bulb to light up (blue bar).
  • the hypothesis that pushing the orange box caused the bulb to light up (orange bar).
  • the hypothesis that pushing both boxes caused the bulb to light up (green bar).

The bar graphs on the left shows the mean likelihood ratings (normalized) of participants in the emotion condition, whereas the bar graphs on the right shows the mean likelihood ratings (normalized) of participants in the no emotion condition. Error bars represent 95% confidence intervals.

6 Hypothesis Testing

6.1 Causal Inferences

Participants in the emotion condition were less likely to infer that the blue box turned on the bulb (\(t(127) = -3.33, p = .001\)), than participants in the no-emotion condition. This is consistent with our postulation (See General Discussion of main paper) that participants in the no emotion condition were less likely to discount the “blue box” hypothesis as they were less motivated to explain the absence of an outcome compared to the participants in the emotion condition who were motivated to explain the agent’s failure.

t.test(relationBlue ~ condition, ecl_dat)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  relationBlue by condition
## t = -3.3326, df = 127, p-value = 0.001128
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group emotion and group no-emotion is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.904819 -0.485496
## sample estimates:
##    mean in group emotion mean in group no-emotion 
##                 2.576271                 3.771429

As expected, participants in the emotion condition were more likely to infer that the orange box turned on the bulb (\(t(120.63) = 3.06, p = .003\)), than participants in the no-emotion condition. We explained that participants in the emotion condition saw the agent’s first action (pushing blue box) as a mistake and hence, gave higher likelihood to the other box (orange box).

t.test(relationOrange ~ condition, ecl_dat)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  relationOrange by condition
## t = 3.0589, df = 120.63, p-value = 0.002737
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group emotion and group no-emotion is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4597069 2.1465885
## sample estimates:
##    mean in group emotion mean in group no-emotion 
##                 6.474576                 5.171429

Also, participants in the emotion condition were less likely to infer that pushing both boxes turned on the bulb (\(t(100.42) = -3.51, p = .007\)), than participants in the no-emotion condition. We explained that participants in the no-emotion condition assumed that both of the agent’s actions were intended and hence, inferred through the agent’s knowledge that both boxes were causally important to turn on the bulb.

t.test(relationOrangeBlue ~ condition, ecl_dat)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  relationOrangeBlue by condition
## t = -3.5147, df = 100.42, p-value = 0.000662
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group emotion and group no-emotion is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.7739279 -0.4938687
## sample estimates:
##    mean in group emotion mean in group no-emotion 
##                 6.966102                 8.100000

6.2 Belief Inferences

On belief inference, participants in the emotion condition were more likely to infer that the agent expected the blue box to turn on the bulb (\(t(125.76) = 5.09, p < .001\)) than participants in the no-emotion condition. This is consistent with our interpretation that participants in the emotion condition inferred that the agent expected that pushing the blue box would turn on the bulb, hence leading to his initial failed action.

t.test(expBlue ~ condition, ecl_dat)
##

Participants in the emotion condition were less likely to infer that the agent expected both boxes to turn on the bulb (\(t(116.91) = -3.56, p < 0.001\)) than participants in the no-emotion condition. 6.3 Desire Inferences

With regards to desire inference, it did not statistically differ across conditions. From the means, we can see that participants in both conditions inferred that the agent likely desired to turn on the bulb.

These ratings describe the non-normalized desire ratings collected on a Likert scale (from 1 to 9).

ecl_dat %>%
  group_by(condition) %>%
  summarise(
    desire = paste0(round(mean(desire, na.rm = T),2)," (",round(sd(desire, na.rm = T),2), ")")
  )

6.4 Knowledge Inferences

Finally, with regards to knowledge inference, participants in the emotion condition were less likely to infer that the agent was knowledgeable about how to turn on the bulb (\(t(116.43) = -5.33, p < .001\)) than participants in the no-emotion condition. This makes sense as the agent in the emotion condition signalled that he failed his initial action (pushing the blue box).

t.test(knowledge1 ~ condition, ecl_dat)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test

## sample estimates:

These ratings describe the non-normalized knowledge ratings collected on a Likert scale (from 1 to 9).
